cs.GT, cs.DS, cs.SI, cs.IT, cs.LG. 

The paper deals with a game-theoretic model of network creation, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.GT (Game Theory) category. The use of edge swaps to form a graph suggests that it could also belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) category. The focus on local information and the inability of players to compute their cost or best response suggests that it could belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) category. The analysis of convergence and Price of Anarchy suggests that it could belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) category. Finally, the use of equilibrium concepts and optimization suggests that it could belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) category.
